INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '87f3609b-b0e7-4437-8ec2-70e588733ea1',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Svelte Feature Folders — Colocation, Barrel Exports, and the $lib Alias$escape$,
  $escape$Feature-based structure in SvelteKit means organizing under `src/lib/features/` by domain, not by type. Each feature owns its `.svelte` components, stores, server utilities, and types — colocated in one directory.

A barrel `index.ts` per feature exposes only its public surface. SvelteKit's `$lib` alias then makes imports clean and refactor-safe: `import { AuthForm, authStore } from '$lib/features/auth'`.

Keep `src/routes/` for routing shells only. `+page.svelte` files should import from feature libs — no business logic, no store declarations directly in route files. This keeps pages thin and features portable.

With Svelte 5, rune-based state lives in `.svelte.ts` files (not plain `.ts`), because `$state` and `$derived` are compile-time transforms. Name them `auth.store.svelte.ts` and barrel-export them the same way — the consumer never needs to care about the file extension.

Avoid god stores in `src/lib/stores.ts`. Colocated stores per feature prevent unrelated reactive dependencies from coupling across the app, and tree-shaking eliminates unused slices automatically.$escape$,
  $escape$// src/lib/features/auth/auth.store.svelte.ts
let user = $state<AuthUser | null>(null);
let loading = $state(false);

export const authStore = {
  get user() { return user; },
  get loading() { return loading; },
  async login(email: string) {
    loading = true;
    user = await fetchUser(email);
    loading = false;
  }
};

// src/lib/features/auth/index.ts
export { default as AuthForm } from './AuthForm.svelte';
export { authStore } from './auth.store.svelte';
export type { AuthUser } from './auth.types';$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
