INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '12aeae94-48b0-4741-8d05-264c6b98e3dc',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Svelte Security — {@html}, Token Storage, and Input Sanitization$escape$,
  $escape$Svelte's {@html} tag is the direct equivalent of React's dangerouslySetInnerHTML — and equally dangerous. Passing unsanitized user content through it opens XSS vectors immediately. Always pipe through DOMPurify before rendering: {@html DOMPurify.sanitize(userContent)}. Never skip this for markdown renderers or comment systems.

For token storage, avoid localStorage for JWTs in Svelte apps. Scripts injected via XSS can trivially read localStorage. Prefer httpOnly cookies managed server-side. If you use SvelteKit, store session tokens in the server-side load() context and pass only non-sensitive derived state to the client via $page.data.

For form inputs, Svelte's two-way binding (bind:value) doesn't sanitize on its own — it just syncs the DOM value. Validate and sanitize in your form submission handler or in a SvelteKit form action using a schema library like Zod. In +page.server.ts actions, treat every field.get() value as untrusted. Svelte's reactivity model makes it easy to forget that $derived and $state are just JS — they carry whatever data you put in.$escape$,
  $escape$<!-- XSS-safe HTML rendering in Svelte -->
<script lang="ts">
  import DOMPurify from 'dompurify';

  let { rawHtml }: { rawHtml: string } = $props();
  const safeHtml = $derived(DOMPurify.sanitize(rawHtml));
</script>

{@html safeHtml}

<!-- SvelteKit form action — treat all input as untrusted -->
// +page.server.ts
export const actions = {
  default: async ({ request }) => {
    const data = await request.formData();
    const comment = z.string().max(500).parse(data.get('comment'));
    // safe to persist
  }
};$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
