INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '97b00980-cc76-4938-a4e4-90f4bc07aaa9',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Svelte Animation — CSS for State, Spring Stores for Motion, and prefers-reduced-motion$escape$,
  $escape$Svelte's built-in primitives cover most animation needs without third-party libraries. For simple state changes — hover, focus, disabled — use CSS transitions via Svelte's `class:` directive or `style:` bindings. Zero JS overhead, no reactivity cost.

For complex motion, `svelte/motion` ships `tweened` (duration + easing) and `spring` (physics via `stiffness`/`damping`). Pair these with the `transition:` directive (`fly`, `fade`, `slide`, `crossfade`) for enter/exit choreography. Framer Motion is React-only — Motion One is the closest framework-agnostic alternative, but Svelte's built-ins handle 90% of cases.

Always gate animation intensity on `prefers-reduced-motion`. In Svelte 5, `MediaQuery` from `svelte/reactivity` gives a reactive, SSR-safe handle. Feed `reduced.current` into `tweened`'s `duration` and your `transition:` params — set both to `0` when reduced is active. Avoid duplicating conditional markup; keep the logic in the motion config itself. This makes `prefers-reduced-motion` a first-class citizen in your motion layer, not an afterthought.$escape$,
  $escape$<script>
  import { tweened } from 'svelte/motion';
  import { fly } from 'svelte/transition';
  import { MediaQuery } from 'svelte/reactivity';
  import { cubicOut } from 'svelte/easing';

  const reduced = new MediaQuery('(prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)');
  const progress = tweened(0, {
    duration: reduced.current ? 0 : 500,
    easing: cubicOut,
  });

  let visible = $state(false);
</script>

{#if visible}
  <div transition:fly={{ y: reduced.current ? 0 : 24, duration: reduced.current ? 0 : 300 }}>
    Animated content
  </div>
{/if}

<progress value={$progress} max={1} />$escape$,
  $escape$javascript$escape$,
