INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'ab691fa7-38d9-4802-a417-80f7f128f4e4',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Svelte's Reactivity Model — Compiler-Driven, Not Runtime-Tracked$escape$,
  $escape$Svelte's reactivity is fundamentally different from React, Vue, and Solid. React re-renders entire components on setState, relying on a virtual DOM diff. Vue uses runtime Proxy objects to intercept reads/writes, building a dependency graph at runtime. Solid is similar to Vue but more granular — signals track subscriptions at the expression level. Svelte does none of this at runtime.

The Svelte compiler statically analyzes your `.svelte` file and rewrites assignments into invalidation calls. When you write `count++`, the compiler emits `$$invalidate('count', count++)`. There's no Proxy, no virtual DOM, no subscription tracking at runtime — just direct DOM mutations keyed to specific variables.

This means reactivity in Svelte 4 is assignment-triggered: mutating an array with `.push()` won't update the DOM unless you follow it with a reassignment (`items = items`). Svelte 5 runes (`$state`, `$derived`) shift this to an explicit signal model — closer to Solid — but still compile away to lean, direct DOM updates. Understanding the compiler's role explains both Svelte's performance ceiling and its edge cases.$escape$,
  $escape$<!-- Svelte 5: runes-based reactivity -->
<script>
  let count = $state(0);
  let doubled = $derived(count * 2);

  // $effect runs when its reactive deps change
  $effect(() => {
    console.log('count changed:', count);
  });
</script>

<button onclick={() => count++}>
  Count: {count} — Doubled: {doubled}
</button>$escape$,
  $escape$javascript$escape$,
